In python there are no `{}` curly brackets to identify code blocks, when you change indentation you move your code to inner or outer block

So the difference between

    if playerhp &lt;= 10:
        playerhp = 10
        print(&quot;Enemy strikes for: &quot;, dmg, &quot;. And your heath is: &quot;, playerhp)


And

    if playerhp &lt;= 10:
        playerhp = 10
    print(&quot;Enemy strikes for: &quot;, dmg, &quot;. And your heath is: &quot;, playerhp)

Could be seen as the difference between

    if (playerhp&gt;=10){
       playerhp=10;
       print ...
    }

and

    if (playerhp&gt;=10){
       playerhp=10; 
    }
    print ...

